The '''Algeria national football team''' ({{langx|ar|منتخب الْجَزَائِر لِكُرَّةُ الْقَدَم}}) represents [[Algeria]] in men's international [[Association football|football]], and is governed by the [[Algerian Football Federation]]. The team plays its home matches at [[Nelson Mandela Stadium]] in Algiers and [[Miloud Hadefi Stadium]] in Oran. Algeria joined [[FIFA]] on 1 January 1964, a year and a half [[Algerian War|after gaining independence]].

The North African team has qualified for five [[FIFA World Cup]]s, in [[1982 FIFA World Cup|1982]], [[1986 FIFA World Cup|1986]], [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010]], [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014]], and [[2026 FIFA World Cup|2026]]. Algeria has won the [[Africa Cup of Nations]] twice, as hosts in [[1990 Africa Cup of Nations|1990]], and again in [[Egypt]] in [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations|2019]]. They were also champions of the [[1975 Mediterranean Games|men's football tournament of the 1975 Mediterranean Games]],  the [[Football at the 1978 All-Africa Games|men's football tournament of the 1978 All-Africa Games]], the [[1991 Afro-Asian Cup of Nations]], and the [[2021 FIFA Arab Cup]].

Algeria has rivalries with [[Egypt national football team|Egypt]], [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]], and [[Tunisia national football team|Tunisia]], while competitive matches have been played against [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]], especially in the 1980s, and [[Mali national football team|Mali]] due to [[Algeria–Mali border|sharing a common border]] and a long-standing competitive rivalry, and against [[Senegal national football team|Senegal]]. For the Algerians, their biggest victory on the world stage was their 2–1 win against [[Germany national football team|West Germany]] during the [[1982 FIFA World Cup]], and in [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014]], Algeria became the first African team to score at least four goals in a match at a World Cup, doing so against [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]].